article_title: Rescue workers race the clock ahead of Elsa
meta_description: As Tropical Storm Elsa approached, Florida rescue workers raced to find bodies in the rubble of the collapsed condo in Surfside. The controlled demolition of the remainder of the building on Sunday night enabled rescuers to expand their search, officials said, but the approaching storm now threatens recovery efforts at the site where crews have sifted through rubble for 12 days in the hopes of finding survivors. Surfside Mayor Charles Burkett described the tough conditions rescue workers are enduring: "The wind is hampering the large cranes, moving very heavy debris. That's a challenge that they're attempting to work around right now."Although forecasts predicted that the Surfside area should avoid the brunt of Elsa on its projected course north from Cuba, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast and could hinder the search-and-rescue effort. Elsa moved past the Florida Keys on Tuesday morning and headed toward the west coast of the state, where it was expected to make landfall on Wednesday morning after dumping heavy rain over Cuba. Elsa has already killed at least three people and caused damage to infrastructure and agriculture in Caribbean islands southeast of Cuba, such as St Lucia and the Dominican Republic.
